because they have
this interesting

00:17:23.200 --> 00:17:26.240 align:middle line:84%
view that we are infinitely
interconnected with each other.

00:17:26.240 --> 00:17:27.040 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:17:27.040 --> 00:17:30.700 align:middle line:84%
You and I, Corinne, have done
this TV show billions of times

00:17:30.700 --> 00:17:32.410 align:middle line:90%
in trillions of former lives.

00:17:32.410 --> 00:17:35.140 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to do it
again another million times

00:17:35.140 --> 00:17:36.160 align:middle line:90%
in future lives.

00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:38.800 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, we'll never
get out of each other's face,

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:39.910 align:middle line:90%
in the Buddhist view.

00:17:39.910 --> 00:17:43.420 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, we should try to
make the best of our interaction

00:17:43.420 --> 00:17:45.220 align:middle line:84%
so that the next time
it's even better,

00:17:45.220 --> 00:17:46.560 align:middle line:90%
the next time it's even better.

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:49.630 align:middle line:84%
Instead, if I blow you
off or you blow me off,

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:53.430 align:middle line:84%
then next life we come
back and we're mad as hell.

00:17:53.430 --> 00:17:55.070 align:middle line:90%
And it's much worse, you see.

00:17:55.070 --> 00:17:58.660 align:middle line:84%
So Buddhism has this gentle
nonviolent thing of feeling

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:01.330 align:middle line:84%
infinitely connected
with everybody.

00:18:01.330 --> 00:18:04.100 align:middle line:84%
And so therefore, you kind
of make the best of them.

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:06.100 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand, if
someone really drives you

00:18:06.100 --> 00:18:09.550 align:middle line:84%
up the war in the short run and
you can't cultivate yourself,

00:18:09.550 --> 00:18:13.390 align:middle line:84%
because they make you so jumpy,
then it's better to avoid them.

00:18:13.390 --> 00:18:15.340 align:middle line:84%
Discretion is the
better part of valor.

00:18:15.340 --> 00:18:17.790 align:middle line:84%
Buddhism is really very
much commonsensical stuff,

00:18:17.790 --> 00:18:22.220 align:middle line:84%
but enforced with scientific
psychological technology.

00:18:22.220 --> 00:18:24.940 align:middle line:84%
>> You know one of the things
that I thought was interesting

00:18:24.940 --> 00:18:28.960 align:middle line:84%
about your book is you have a
whole big section here on what

00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:31.488 align:middle line:84%
you call a ideal
political platform.

00:18:31.488 --> 00:18:32.530 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right, Corinne.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:35.740 align:middle line:84%
It's my enlightenment party
platform for the year 2000.

00:18:35.740 --> 00:18:37.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Do you think it
will ever happen?

00:18:37.570 --> 00:18:39.300 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes, of course, it will.

00:18:39.300 --> 00:18:41.650 align:middle line:84%
It might not this
planet, this year

00:18:41.650 --> 00:18:44.380 align:middle line:84%
2000, but maybe the next
planet, the next year 2000.

00:18:44.380 --> 00:18:45.890 align:middle line:90%
Sooner or later, it will happen.

00:18:45.890 --> 00:18:47.682 align:middle line:84%
>> You know what I
liked was the one part--

00:18:47.682 --> 00:18:50.620 align:middle line:84%
you have to pay taxes under
your political platform,

00:18:50.620 --> 00:18:54.050 align:middle line:84%
but you get to choose
what your taxes support.

00:18:54.050 --> 00:18:54.850 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:18:54.850 --> 00:18:56.725 align:middle line:84%
>> And you give the
government three choices.

00:18:56.725 --> 00:18:57.525 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:18:57.525 --> 00:18:58.640 align:middle line:90%
>> I loved that.

00:18:58.640 --> 00:18:59.440 align:middle line:90%
>> Isn't that nice?

00:18:59.440 --> 00:19:00.240 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes.

00:19:00.240 --> 00:19:01.960 align:middle line:90%
>> It's a consensual tax system.

00:19:01.960 --> 00:19:04.570 align:middle line:84%
And it's sort of like voting
for where it should go.

00:19:04.570 --> 00:19:05.950 align:middle line:84%
You say I want it
to go for this.

00:19:05.950 --> 00:19:07.960 align:middle line:84%
Some people would want
to pay for defense.

00:19:07.960 --> 00:19:10.150 align:middle line:84%
Some people will want to
pay for schools and not

00:19:10.150 --> 00:19:11.125 align:middle line:90%
for defense, et cetera.

00:19:11.125 --> 00:19:13.000 align:middle line:84%
And if you give people
the sense that they're

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000 align:middle line:84%
supporting what they want,
then you'll have more

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.230 align:middle line:90%
cheerful taxpayers, we hope.

00:19:17.230 --> 00:19:20.710 align:middle line:84%
>> And the fact that Buddhism
really does not support

00:19:20.710 --> 00:19:22.720 align:middle line:84%
anything like
capital punishment.

00:19:22.720 --> 00:19:24.430 align:middle line:90%
>> No, Buddhism is nonviolent.

00:19:24.430 --> 00:19:26.423 align:middle line:90%
It's against violence.

00:19:26.423 --> 00:19:28.340 align:middle line:84%
That doesn't mean,
Corinne, that, for example,

00:19:28.340 --> 00:19:31.510 align:middle line:84%
if some maniac is about
to kill your family

00:19:31.510 --> 00:19:33.100 align:middle line:84%
and the only way
you can stop them--

00:19:33.100 --> 00:19:35.980 align:middle line:84%
if you happen to have a
weapon-- is kill them.

00:19:35.980 --> 00:19:38.320 align:middle line:84%
Actually, although it's
a sin to kill them,

00:19:38.320 --> 00:19:40.630 align:middle line:84%
and you shouldn't do it
with hatred in your heart,

00:19:40.630 --> 00:19:42.670 align:middle line:84%
you should move energetically
and blow them away

00:19:42.670 --> 00:19:45.310 align:middle line:84%
to save your family
in self-defense.

00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:47.230 align:middle line:84%
Capital punishment
is unpleasant,

00:19:47.230 --> 00:19:49.540 align:middle line:84%
because you already
have them under arrest,

00:19:49.540 --> 00:19:50.830 align:middle line:90%
under confinement.

00:19:50.830 --> 00:19:53.560 align:middle line:84%
And you could actually use
every educational method

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:56.800 align:middle line:84%
at that your
psychology knows to try

00:19:56.800 --> 00:19:59.350 align:middle line:84%
to rehabilitate them and make
them genuinely repentant,

00:19:59.350 --> 00:20:01.420 align:middle line:84%
and make them genuinely
kind, and make up for it

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:02.800 align:middle line:90%
to the world and all this.

00:20:02.800 --> 00:20:04.870 align:middle line:84%
And yet, when they're
in your power like that

00:20:04.870 --> 00:20:06.700 align:middle line:84%
and they really can't
hurt another person,

00:20:06.700 --> 00:20:09.502 align:middle line:84%
you then go and
vindictively kill them.

00:20:09.502 --> 00:20:10.960 align:middle line:84%
That's what Buddhism
really doesn't

00:20:10.960 --> 00:20:12.335 align:middle line:84%
like about that,
because in a way

00:20:12.335 --> 00:20:15.652 align:middle line:84%
it kind of encourages the
killer attitude because it says,

00:20:15.652 --> 00:20:17.110 align:middle line:84%
if you have the
power over somebody

00:20:17.110 --> 00:20:19.567 align:middle line:84%
and you can kill them, well,
you might as well, you see.

00:20:19.567 --> 00:20:22.150 align:middle line:84%
And that's why Buddhism really
objected to capital punishment.

00:20:22.150 --> 00:20:27.170 align:middle line:84%
>> And also the prison reforms
that are not being utilized.

00:20:27.170 --> 00:20:27.970 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:20:27.970 --> 00:20:31.120 align:middle line:84%
Our prisons are too much based
on punishing people rather than

00:20:31.120 --> 00:20:32.890 align:middle line:84%
rehabilitating them,
although we have

00:20:32.890 --> 00:20:34.600 align:middle line:90%
the theory of rehabilitation.

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:37.228 align:middle line:84%
But in Buddhism,
2,000 years ago,

00:20:37.228 --> 00:20:39.520 align:middle line:84%
in certain kingdoms where
they listened to the Buddhist

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:41.470 align:middle line:84%
teachers, they banned
capital punishment

00:20:41.470 --> 00:20:43.840 align:middle line:84%
and they had a
rehabilitated prison system.

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:45.700 align:middle line:84%
And they had the idea
that every prisoner

00:20:45.700 --> 00:20:47.980 align:middle line:84%
should be treated
like a wayward child

00:20:47.980 --> 00:20:51.100 align:middle line:84%
and, therefore, made to
be reeducated and grow up

00:20:51.100 --> 00:20:53.123 align:middle line:84%
in a proper way rather
than being killed off.

00:20:53.123 --> 00:20:54.790 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
very, very important.

00:20:54.790 --> 00:20:58.780 align:middle line:84%
Actually, if I had my way,
Corinne, Columbia University

00:20:58.780 --> 00:21:01.540 align:middle line:84%
or any university
would have a branch

00:21:01.540 --> 00:21:04.180 align:middle line:84%
where the faculty would
teach one course a year

00:21:04.180 --> 00:21:06.483 align:middle line:84%
to some maximum
security prisoners.

00:21:06.483 --> 00:21:07.900 align:middle line:84%
So that anybody
who went to prison

00:21:07.900 --> 00:21:10.510 align:middle line:84%
would be forced to be
educated more and more.

00:21:10.510 --> 00:21:12.490 align:middle line:10%
And all of the junior
professors, all community

00:21:12.490 --> 00:21:14.830 align:middle line:10%
colleges, would be
built next to prisons.

00:21:14.830 --> 00:21:18.220 align:middle line:10%
And that there would be a
major emphasis on reeducating

00:21:18.220 --> 00:21:20.090 align:middle line:10%
as many prisoners as possible.

00:21:20.090 --> 00:21:22.420 align:middle line:84%
I know for a fact from
prison psychologists,

00:21:22.420 --> 00:21:24.700 align:middle line:84%
I've studied it a little
bit, the one thing that

00:21:24.700 --> 00:21:27.522 align:middle line:84%
lowers the recidivism rate
of prisoners who are released

00:21:27.522 --> 00:21:29.230 align:middle line:84%
and then commit more
crimes and come back

00:21:29.230 --> 00:21:31.300 align:middle line:84%
is if there's some sort
of educational program

00:21:31.300 --> 00:21:33.700 align:middle line:84%
in that prison where
they gain a trade.

00:21:33.700 --> 00:21:34.570 align:middle line:90%
They gain knowledge.

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:35.860 align:middle line:90%
They learn some skill.

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:37.240 align:middle line:90%
They read, et cetera.

00:21:37.240 --> 00:21:40.090 align:middle line:84%
It's gaining a sense of control
over their own minds and lives

00:21:40.090 --> 00:21:42.850 align:middle line:84%
through being educated is the
one thing that saves people

00:21:42.850 --> 00:21:43.990 align:middle line:90%
from a life of crime.

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:47.170 align:middle line:84%
And we're very short-sighted
nowadays because of demagogic

00:21:47.170 --> 00:21:49.850 align:middle line:84%
politicians who say
like these commercials--

00:21:49.850 --> 00:21:50.650 align:middle line:90%
>> Lock them up.

00:21:50.650 --> 00:21:52.710 align:middle line:84%
>> --where they slam
prison doors and stuff.

00:21:52.710 --> 00:21:54.460 align:middle line:84%
And they act like that
solved the problem.

00:21:54.460 --> 00:21:58.030 align:middle line:84%
Meanwhile, it costs
us $60,000 a year

00:21:58.030 --> 00:21:59.860 align:middle line:84%
to keep someone
locked up in a prison,

00:21:59.860 --> 00:22:02.200 align:middle line:84%
twice the tuition at
Harvard or Columbia.

00:22:02.200 --> 00:22:04.270 align:middle line:84%
>> When are you going
to run for office?

00:22:04.270 --> 00:22:06.733 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, not for
a while, Corinne,

00:22:06.733 --> 00:22:09.150 align:middle line:84%
because I don't think they're
ready for a Buddhist studies

00:22:09.150 --> 00:22:10.710 align:middle line:90%
professor.

00:22:10.710 --> 00:22:12.510 align:middle line:84%
But I'd be happy
if Ross Perot would

00:22:12.510 --> 00:22:17.427 align:middle line:84%
like to bankroll me and give me
a platform to explain my ideas.

00:22:17.427 --> 00:22:19.260 align:middle line:84%
Then at least if I could
be a good influence

00:22:19.260 --> 00:22:22.510 align:middle line:84%
on Al Gore or the young
Bush, the new Bush, whoever

00:22:22.510 --> 00:22:24.182 align:middle line:84%
is going to run,
whoever might win,

00:22:24.182 --> 00:22:25.890 align:middle line:84%
then I'd be happy to
have that influence.

00:22:25.890 --> 00:22:28.800 align:middle line:84%
Because one of the
things, I think, I feel,

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:31.140 align:middle line:84%
that holds our
politicians back is

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:34.828 align:middle line:84%
that the public is kind of
too complacent and apathetic.

00:22:34.828 --> 00:22:36.870 align:middle line:84%
And the public has this
attitude that they're all

00:22:36.870 --> 00:22:38.790 align:middle line:84%
going to do nothing
worthwhile, a,

00:22:38.790 --> 00:22:42.240 align:middle line:84%
and, b, that there's nothing you
can do about almost anything.

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:45.960 align:middle line:84%
And that is a very negative
attitude that causes us--

00:22:45.960 --> 00:22:48.030 align:middle line:84%
in the past, when America
has succeeded well

00:22:48.030 --> 00:22:51.090 align:middle line:84%
and things is when we've had
the attitude that we can succeed

00:22:51.090 --> 00:22:51.930 align:middle line:90%
and then we have.

00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:53.108 align:middle line:90%
>> Thank you so much.

00:22:53.108 --> 00:22:54.400 align:middle line:90%
I'll vote for you when you run.

00:22:54.400 --> 00:22:54.750 align:middle line:90%
>> All right.

00:22:54.750 --> 00:22:55.550 align:middle line:90%
Thank you, Corinne.

00:22:55.550 --> 00:22:57.630 align:middle line:90%
